===Verb===
{{en-verb|chanc|ing}}

# {{archaic|intransitive}} To [[happen]] by chance, to [[occur]].
#: ''It '''chanced''' that I found a solution the very next day.''
#* '''1843''', [[w:Thomas_Carlyle|Thomas Carlyle]], ''[[:w:Past and Present (book)|Past and Present]]'', book 2, ch. XV, ''Practical — Devotional''
#*: Once […] it '''chanced''' that Geoffrey Riddell [[:w:Bishop of Ely|Bishop of Ely]], a Prelate rather troublesome to [[:w:Samson of Tottington|our Abbot]], made a request of him for timber from his woods towards certain edifices going on at [[:w:Glemsford|Glemsford]].
#* '''1847''', {{w|Charlotte Brontë}}, {{w|Jane Eyre}}, Chapter XVIII
#*: Mr. Mason, shivering as some one '''chanced''' to open the door, asked for more coal to be put on the fire, which had burnt out its flame, though its mass of cinder still shone hot and red. The footman who brought the coal, in going out, stopped near Mr. Eshton's chair, and said something to him in a low voice, of which I heard only the words, "old woman,"—"quite troublesome."
# To [[try]] or [[risk]].
#: ''Shall we carry the umbrella, or '''chance''' it?''
# To [[discover]] something by [[chance]].
#: ''He '''chanced''' upon a kindly stranger who showed him the way.''

